{"author":"Iso Tester","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Repo-snapshot isolation for code-reading gates\n\n## Context\n\nThe rebar MCP server is a long-lived process pinned to ONE working directory. Every operation\nthat reads PROJECT SOURCE CODE (the LLM gates) reads whatever branch + uncommitted changes\nhappen to be in that checkout at call time. This session hit it: a completion-verifier read\nthe wrong branch (a parallel task had switched the shared checkout) and produced a FALSE-\nNEGATIVE on work correctly merged to main. Broader problem: an MCP server used by a DISTRIBUTED\nTEAM concurrently cannot have all gates read one mutable working tree, and an HMAC-signed\nverdict computed against a moving branch is not reproducible. Design grounded against Gitaly,\nSourcegraph gitserver/zoekt, GitHub tarball API, Bazel, ccache, Nix, in-toto.\n\n## What\n\nEvery code-reading op accepts `ref` (branch|tag|SHA, default `origin/main`) + `source` mode:\n- **attested** (default): fetch -> resolve ref to immutable SHA -> faithful lock-free\n  materialization into a content-addressed snapshot -> run gate -> record `verified_at_sha`\n  and bind it via the EXISTING SIGNED MANIFEST CHANNEL (a manifest step, NOT a payload-schema\n  change — so no PAYLOAD_VERSION bump, no invalidation of prior signatures; see S4). Reproducible.\n- **local** (opt-in): read the server's in-place checkout (possibly dirty); NEVER signs.\n\n## Children (de-risking order)\n\nRiskiest piece first — the lock-free portable snapshot primitive — then build outward:\n1. S1 `hoot-glove-foyer` (6d56) — faithful, lock-free materialization core (the primitive).\n2. S2 `clay-feast-strife` (70c7) — content-addressed cache + janitor (the hard reclamation part).\n3. S3 `pale-peer-hawk` (fa49) — thread ref+source through the 5 gates (depends on S1).\n4. S4 `ill-hazel-probe` (30b3) — attested signing via the manifest channel (depends on S3).\n5. S5 `harm-shove-gate` (b7fa) — CLI + MCP surfaces (depends on S3).\n6. S6 `vain-weed-rave` (1ba5) — docs (depends on S4, S5).\nBlocking edges encode this DAG. A thin vertical slice (S1 + one gate re-rooted end-to-end)\nshould prove the snapshot primitive before the horizontal sweep across all five gates.\n\n## Out of scope\n\nSparse archiving; verdict memoization; auto ticket->commit provenance (REB-289); diff-base\n(base+head) for code-review (single ref/snapshot like the others); serverless lifecycle (AWS\nvolume placement + EFS/NFS flock caveat tracked on alto-fruit-punch).\n\n## Architecture decision record\n\nThe novel cross-cutting patterns (content-addressed snapshot layout, delete-on-last-close\nreader safety, flock GC interlock, read-tree+checkout-index over `git archive`, dropping the\nrejected PID+heartbeat lease, manifest-channel SHA binding) are captured in an ADR (authored\nin S2/S4) so future maintainers see the decision + rejected alternatives.\n\n## Success Criteria\n\nEvery code-reading gate verifies a client-specified, immutable, reproducible snapshot at a\npinned SHA — never the server's mutable checkout — safely under concurrent distributed use;\nsigned verdicts bind `verified_at_sha` via the manifest channel (reproducible, no prior-\nsignature breakage); local mode preserves the single-developer \"verify before push\" workflow.\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] No code-reading gate reads the server's working tree in attested mode; all read a\n      faithful snapshot materialized at the pinned SHA.\n- [ ] A signed verdict binds `verified_at_sha` via the signed manifest channel (no payload-\n      schema/version change; prior signatures still verify) and is reproducible against that SHA.\n- [ ] `local` source mode reads the in-place checkout and CANNOT produce a signed verdict;\n      source=local is the documented back-out that restores the prior in-place read behavior.\n- [ ] Concurrent gates on the same and different SHAs run without git-lock contention or\n      cross-op corruption; the snapshot cache + janitor reclaim disk under a defined free-space\n      watermark (S2) without disrupting in-flight reads.\n- [ ] Private-repo fetch failures surface a descriptive, actionable credential error.\n- [ ] Portable across macOS + Linux (no external tar; no hardcoded /tmp; flock+mkdir fallback).\n- [ ] Operational tunables (free-space watermark, default ref, grace/age windows) are\n      configurable with documented defaults (S2/S3).\n- [ ] An ADR captures the architecture + rejected alternatives (PID-lease, payload-schema SHA binding).\n- [ ] All six enumerated child stories (S1-S6 above) closed; `make lint` + full test suite green."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1782529601605455001,"uuid":"c5b6cf4e-cf57-424b-bb1a-1bed0ff5886f"}